01:35.180 --> 01:44.900
Stories for that month jumped right off the stand, grabbed hold of me, said,
take me home little boy, you will love me, and it will become a way of life. And

01:44.900 --> 01:55.600
in those early days there was just the one magazine a month, and it was like a
man in a desert who sees an oasis. You know, you head for any drop of water you

01:55.600 --> 02:07.120
can find. I began combing the magazine markets looking at the mundane
periodicals. In Liberty Magazine occasionally I found something new by H.G.

02:07.300 --> 02:19.380
Wells or Sax Rohmer with his Fu Manchu super scientific villain. And in the
pages of Argosy I discovered that this magazine, besides having westerns and

02:19.380 --> 02:30.360
romance and air war and whatnot, that they generally had some science fiction
going. Some of the pioneer authors of Ray Cummings and R.F. Starzl and Victor

02:30.360 --> 02:44.020
Russo, and there was a lot of Burroughs, Mars and Venus and Pellucidar and
those, and also in Blue Book Magazine. By 1930 we had about seven magazines. We

02:44.020 --> 02:54.700
had the amazing quarterlies in addition to the monthlies, and Science Wonder had
come along, which also had a quarterly publication, and Air Wonder, and then

02:54.700 --> 03:04.860
there was Astounding Stories of Super Science started up, which is still going
today under the modified title Analog Science Fiction. And that original Amazing

03:04.860 --> 03:19.820
from April 1926 is still being published and in my collection. By 1929, my rather
mundane mother began, had begun to be somewhat worried about my collecting

03:19.820 --> 03:29.600
instincts. She had counted my magazines, said, Son, do you realize you have 27
of these magazines? Now if you continue at that rate till you were a grown man,

03:29.740 --> 03:40.480
why, you might have 100 magazines. Well, my dear mother lived till nearly 94 and
was in my own home at the end of her life. The home was now four stories, 17

03:40.480 --> 03:50.580
rooms, three garages in which you couldn't park a toothpick, because we
eliminated the cars from them and put in shelves, and that is totaled with the

03:50.580 --> 03:57.980
Science Fiction collections. As a matter of fact, whenever I see a garage sale
nowadays, I buy another garage. I have two extra garages that are filling up

03:57.980 --> 04:09.180
around Los Angeles. So the collection has grown from that one single magazine
back in October 1926. Here I am on the verge of my 55th anniversary in the

04:09.180 --> 04:23.760
field. Now there are 300,000 magazines and books and manuscripts and props from
movies and artwork and stills. It's just, I stop at nothing, I even try to get

04:23.760 --> 04:25.480
space stamps from all over the world.

04:28.400 --> 04:35.980
It wouldn't be any stretch of the imagination to say that you have probably the
most complete collection of Science Fiction anywhere. Well, let's put it this

04:35.980 --> 04:45.000
way. I've been on both sides of the Iron Curtain. I've been upside down in
Tasmania. I've been a thousand miles from the North Pole. I've been in Hungary

04:45.000 --> 04:56.320
and Czechoslovakia and East Germany. I've been to Japan and if there's any
greater collection, it must be underground or well hidden. Naturally, I'm so

04:56.320 --> 05:06.420
intensely interested in the subject matter that I seek out collectors everywhere
in the world. There are maybe half a dozen of us who have equal collections of

05:06.420 --> 05:20.660
magazines, that is to say about 99% complete. And there are certainly collectors
with enormous numbers of books. But I go beyond that into autographs of the

05:20.660 --> 05:30.920
authors and the motion picture people. I would have Bela Lugosi would sign Count
