14:35.720 --> 14:37.920
Mr. Ackerman, I have a two-part question.

14:39.200 --> 14:42.600
Number one, you have written science fiction because I've read the stories.

14:43.140 --> 14:47.440
The first part of the question would be why you didn't continue as an author.

14:48.260 --> 14:55.620
And secondly, I can't think of any other field where there's such a unique and intimate relationship between fans and writers.

14:56.540 --> 14:57.980
I wonder why that is so.

14:59.460 --> 15:07.960
Well, when I was a kid, when I was in high school, I edited the high school newspaper and the annual publication.

15:08.180 --> 15:10.800
I carried on much the same way in college.

15:11.100 --> 15:15.560
And I firmly believed that I would grow up to be a science fiction writer.

15:15.740 --> 15:26.720
But when I got around to writing, I searched my mind and I was a little chagrin to find that I wasn't going to be another H.G. Wells or O.F. Stapledon

15:26.720 --> 15:28.460
or Arthur C. Clarke.

15:28.520 --> 15:33.300
I guess I had to set two grandiose ideals for myself.

15:33.680 --> 15:41.800
I just expected somehow or other I got to be 20, 25 or 30 that I would be bubbling over with books like Childhood's End

15:41.800 --> 15:45.940
and The Shape of Things to Come and The Best of Heinlein and so on.

15:45.960 --> 15:53.880
And I found... I say I searched my mind and found that I just didn't have these book-length novels in me.

15:53.880 --> 16:00.880
On the other hand, I did seem to excel in the O. Henry type of short, short story.

16:01.060 --> 16:06.400
And I finally wrote the world's shortest published science fiction story.

16:07.320 --> 16:15.940
Ray Bradbury, whose first story I had edited and published in 1938, had called me up some years later in a great state of excitement.

16:16.140 --> 16:19.320
He said, For you, I just sold a story for one dollar a word.

16:19.320 --> 16:23.200
Every little A and the but or hum hum.

16:23.780 --> 16:25.320
Well, I kind of mentally gave up.

16:25.420 --> 16:26.940
I thought, Oh my God, a dollar a word.

16:27.120 --> 16:29.960
I would never reach that altitude.

16:30.640 --> 16:39.720
But 1973, I think I was asked to do a best of the year anthology.

16:39.900 --> 16:45.800
And then looking at all the stories that year, I found a real cute one that I think was just three words long.

16:46.240 --> 16:48.840
So I thought, Well, I can top that.

16:49.020 --> 16:50.640
I can do one that's two words long.

16:50.920 --> 16:55.300
Let's call it World War III and the story is the end.

16:56.400 --> 16:59.460
So after I mentally wrote that, well, it's no use stopping the air.

16:59.600 --> 17:02.700
My mind's well going, write the one word story and be done with it.

17:02.980 --> 17:05.900
And I came up with something I've forgotten in the meantime.

17:06.200 --> 17:07.680
I said, No, no use stopping there.

17:07.760 --> 17:11.020
Somebody will come up with a story that is one letter of the alphabet long.

17:11.160 --> 17:11.880
That better be me.

17:11.880 --> 17:19.320
So I wrote that story and I was paid $100 for a single letter of the alphabet.

17:20.480 --> 17:25.280
I went on to sell the story four more times each time for $100.

17:25.820 --> 17:28.660
So I got $500 for a single letter of the alphabet.

17:29.220 --> 17:36.580
Of course, I retained the translation rights for the story and the movie rights and the comic book rights.

17:36.580 --> 17:43.900
And I very sneakily copied right at the other 26 letters of the alphabet so that nobody could use them for science fiction stories.

17:45.500 --> 17:53.520
And since a normal size word, as an average word is about five letters in length,

17:53.700 --> 18:02.200
in effect I've collected about $2,500 for one word, which perhaps should be again as a world record.

18:02.780 --> 18:09.460
But I say I'm just searching myself, found that apparently I was not a novelist but a short story writer.

18:09.620 --> 18:15.100
And I've done enough of those to have at least one collection way back in 1935.

18:15.100 --> 18:15.920
I think it was.

18:16.160 --> 18:22.280
I collaborated with the Dan Venge's current guest of honor, Catherine Moore, and wrote Nymph of Darkness.

18:24.080 --> 18:29.640
And you were asking why there's such a liaison between the authors and the fans.

18:29.640 --> 18:39.900
I imagine because most authors start out as fans like myself, I remember very well what it was to go to the first world science fiction in 1939,

18:40.980 --> 18:52.260
admiring Ray Cummings and L. Sprague de Camp and Manly Wade Wellman and seeing Virgil Finlay.

18:52.260 --> 19:00.700
And then myself eventually becoming somewhat in the same genre with them.

19:01.860 --> 19:14.700
So I think that Van Vogt and Ray Bradbury and Arthur C. Clarke all perfectly well remember their humble beginnings when they were writing for fanzines.

19:17.180 --> 19:18.320
I've got to go, David.

19:18.980 --> 19:21.460
Thank you, sir. It was a pleasure to meet you.
I've got to ask somebody to ask you.

19:26.440 --> 19:38.740
Okay. Mr. Ackerman, you're known as quite a fan, but to us collectors,

19:38.960 --> 19:47.680
you're also known as the ultimate collector. When did you start collecting
science fiction, and what was your first goal, and how has that goal changed as

19:47.680 --> 19:59.420
far as what you're trying to collect? Well, in October 1926, when I first saw a
science fiction magazine, I was only nine years old, and I don't believe I

19:59.420 --> 20:09.580
realized the periodicity of publications. I guess I thought it was some kind of
a one-time phenomenon, and there would never be another amazing stories. And it

20:09.580 --> 20:20.100
wasn't until some months later in 1928 that I saw amazing stories again. Then I
caught on to the fact that if I watched the newsstands carefully, about every

20:20.100 --> 20:35.400
four weeks, there would be more manna from heaven. So I read the magazine so
quickly that there was nothing coming along for another month that I would re

20:35.400 --> 20:49.220
-read the stories. So I hung on to the magazines because they were very precious
to me, and before I knew it, my mother said I had 27 of them. And by about 1930,

20:49.380 --> 21:02.920
I probably had around 100 of them. And one mad moment in my life, during the
Depression, my parents persuaded me to sell my magazines in order to finance new

21:02.920 --> 21:13.600
ones, because 25 cents was kind of tough to come by when men were starving on
the streets trying to make a living selling apples for a nickel. Well, I did

21:13.600 --> 21:28.200
sell my collection, such as it was, about 1930. And before their very eyes, my
parents saw me becoming weak and waned and listless and lost my appetite. And

21:28.200 --> 21:38.080
about 48 hours was all I could take of that. So I said, okay, okay, you know, go
and buy your magazines back if they mean so much to you. And from that day to

21:38.080 --> 21:49.160
this, I have never passed by a magazine. I just buy every single science fiction
fantasy magazine as fast as they are published, have a standing order for every

21:49.160 --> 22:02.440
paperback to be sent to me, go through Publishers Weekly every seven days, and
Locus and any source whatsoever that instances fantasy magazines and books, and

22:02.440 --> 22:10.500
send off for all of them. And then I go through catalogs from all over the
world. And constantly mining the past, you would think that someday you'd say,

22:10.580 --> 22:17.680
well, I've got it all, but there just seems to be no end to it. A perfect
example. I went to the World Science Fiction Convention down in Australia,

22:18.280 --> 22:26.920
walked a half a block from my hotel, and saw a science fiction book in a window.
And I said, well, I don't have it. I suppose it was published here in Australia.

22:27.360 --> 22:36.460
But I went in and I found it was published in New York seven years earlier, and
despite every review I'd read and every list I'd looked at, I hadn't known of it

22:36.460 --> 22:49.100
until that moment. So I feel my collection is incomplete if someone who's
looking at it suddenly says, oh, don't you have? And then I've got 300,000

22:49.100 --> 22:58.940
things, but I don't have this one particular magazine or book, so I guess I'll
have to get it. How has where you've housed the collection through the years

22:58.940 --> 23:12.000
changed from your humble beginnings till now? Well, it started out in San
Francisco. I had, down in the basement, my dad built me a little den, and I was

23:12.000 --> 23:22.840
able to keep everything in one very small room. Then when I moved back to Los
Angeles where I was born, I lived with my maternal grandparents, and they had a

23:22.840 --> 23:36.340
rather large apartment plus three garages. That's where I started filling up
garages. Before I knew it, they were full. And in the hallway in my maternal

23:36.340 --> 23:47.720
grandparents' home, I began stacking books up to the ceiling, and they gave me
one bedroom. And pretty soon it was difficult even to get into bed because it

23:47.720 --> 23:58.720
was totally surrounded. I remember Life magazine came to me 30 years ago in
1951, took a photo of me in that bedroom. And in 1951, I finally moved into my

23:58.720 --> 24:11.400
first home. That had 13 rooms and three garages. And when I totaled that, and I
really mean totaled it, used as many drawers as weren't absolutely necessary for

24:11.400 --> 24:20.260
clothing. They had books and magazines and put them under the beds. And we
didn't need all the bathrooms, so I filled those. And finally, when my wife, the

24:20.260 --> 24:29.360
university professor and science fiction translator, came home and looked in the
refrigerator one day and found the food was gone, replaced by reels of science

24:29.360 --> 24:39.440
fiction movies, she realized the end had come for that home. So for a couple of
years, we lived in an apartment while I used a 13-room home and three garages

24:39.440 --> 24:51.500
totally for my collection. We started all over again eight years ago with a four
-story, 17-room home and the usual three garages. And now that's bursting at the

24:51.500 --> 25:01.300
seams, and I've added two garages that I'm renting around town. Fortunately, the
mayor of Los Angeles has come to my rescue. He discovered me, came out to the

25:01.300 --> 25:11.860
house, had four librarians come and look at everything, and they estimated there
are approximately 300,000 pieces in the collection. And the city of Los Angeles

25:11.860 --> 25:21.920
in the near future is going to create an actual museum. It won't just be a wing
of the library or anything of that sort, but an actual bonafide science fiction

25:21.920 --> 25:32.020
museum that already, when you're three blocks away, the structure of it will
tell the story. It's just, hey, that's got to be the museum. And the grandson of

25:32.020 --> 25:41.760
Edgar Rice Burroughs has already indicated to me when the museum exists, that
he'd be very happy to have an Edgar Rice Burroughs wing in it and make all of

25:41.760 --> 25:55.960
the first editions available and manuscripts and the artwork by J. Allen, St.
John and others. And I think that Hollywood will very much get into the act once

25:55.960 --> 26:07.540
it exists. And in addition to the props I've been able to acquire on my own,
like Bela Lugosi's Dracula cape and Lon Chaney Sr.'s makeup kit and Life Masks

26:07.540 --> 26:21.860
of Karloff and Peter Lorre and John Carradine and Vincent Price and many of the
animated monsters from King Kong and Harryhausen films that I imagine the Star

26:21.860 --> 26:32.760
Wars people and Alien and so on, they will be all quick to contribute because
everybody will want to be represented in something that is available to the

26:32.760 --> 26:44.820
public seven days a week, people for all over the world to come and see
something like Disneyland and Magic Castle and Universal Tour and so on. Is this

26:44.820 --> 26:54.340
something that the City of Los Angeles will sponsor entirely? Well, I think it
will be in two parts. About the 15th of September, I'm going to go down to the

26:54.340 --> 27:06.000
mayor's office. They tell me that they have found a benefactor who is going to
create a cultural center and make the museum a centerpiece of it. It will be one

27:06.000 --> 27:17.120
thing just to move it out of my home. They estimate it will take $125,000 just
to move it to its final resting place. And surely it costs multi-millions of

27:17.120 --> 27:29.260
dollars for the museum itself. And I don't want it just frozen. The day I give
it away, that's it. It never grows. I hope that 200 years after I'm gone that it

27:29.260 --> 27:39.700
will still be up to date that all the magazines and books and posters and
everything will be added. I think the city feels its responsibility will be to

27:39.700 --> 27:57.640
create the housing for it originally. And then they hope to institute what they
call a support committee. that they're going to invite Robert Block, A. E. Van

27:57.640 --> 28:11.740
Vogt, Ray Bradbury, Steven Spielberg, Stephen King, George Lucas, John Landis,
maybe way over there in Sri Lanka, Arthur C. Clarke, all the independently

28:11.740 --> 28:20.740
wealthy science fiction practitioners to see if they would like to pitch in. For
instance, George Lucas, I think, gave something like a million and a half

28:20.740 --> 28:32.360
recently to the university where he had graduated. So some of these high
-powered, financially set people will get in the act and contribute. they'll be

28:32.360 --> 28:43.180
the sponsoring committee to make it possible to go on adding to it. I would like
to see a theater in conjunction with it where you'd be seeing all the classic

28:43.180 --> 29:00.020
movies constantly and to have a fund that I might mastermind as the curator to
purchase fine artwork and something that we should have in such a collection.

